  "prompt": "How can I know if I'm not pregnant without using a test?",
  "response": "If you're trying to determine whether you're pregnant without using a test, you can observe certain signs and symptoms, but these are not definitive and can vary greatly among individuals. Here are some common indicators:\n\n### 1. **Missed Period**\n   - A missed period is often the first sign of pregnancy, especially if your cycle is usually regular. However, stress, hormonal imbalances, or other factors can also cause missed periods.\n\n### 2. **Breast Changes**\n   - Tender, swollen, or sore breasts can occur early in pregnancy due to hormonal changes.\n\n### 3. **Fatigue**\n   - Increased fatigue or feeling unusually tired can be an early sign of pregnancy.\n\n### 4. **Nausea or Morning Sickness**\n   - Nausea, with or without vomiting, is a common symptom of early pregnancy, though it doesn't affect everyone.\n\n### 5. **Frequent Urination**\n   - Needing to urinate more often than usual can be a sign of pregnancy, especially in the first trimester.\n\n### 6. **Food Aversions or Cravings**\n   - Changes in your sense of taste or smell, or sudden cravings or aversions to certain foods, can occur.\n\n### 7. **Mood Swings**\n   - Hormonal changes may lead to mood swings or emotional sensitivity.\n\n### 8. **Basal Body Temperature**\n   - If you track your basal body temperature (BBT), a sustained rise in temperature beyond your usual luteal phase may indicate pregnancy.\n\n### 9. **Implantation Bleeding**\n   - Some people experience light spotting or bleeding when the fertilized egg attaches to the uterine lining, which occurs about 10-14 days after conception.\n\n### 10. **Other Symptoms**\n   - Bloating, constipation, headaches, or mild cramping can also occur in early pregnancy.\n\n### Important Notes:\n- These symptoms can also be caused by other factors, such as hormonal fluctuations, stress, or illness.\n- The only way to confirm pregnancy definitively is through a **pregnancy test** (urine or blood test) or an ultrasound.\n- If you suspect you might be pregnant, consult a healthcare provider for accurate testing and guidance.\n\nIf you're trying to avoid pregnancy or are concerned about your reproductive health, consider discussing contraception options or planning with a healthcare professional.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
